      "teaching": "First Samuel opens at a theological and institutional crisis that mirrors the end of Judges. The tabernacle is at Shiloh. The high priest is Eli, an old man whose two sons — Hophni and Phinehas — are described in 2:12 as 'scoundrels' who 'had no regard for the Lord.' They take the best portions of the sacrifices before the fat is burned — the portion belonging to God — and they sleep with the women who serve at the entrance to the tent of meeting. The priesthood that was supposed to mediate between a holy God and a sinful people is itself corrupt at its highest levels. The institution has failed.\n\nInto this institutional failure comes Hannah — a private woman with a private grief. She is one of two wives of Elkanah; the other wife, Peninnah, has children and 'provoked her year after year' because Hannah was barren. The family goes annually to Shiloh for the yearly sacrifice, and year after year the provocation intensifies. Hannah's grief is physical: she wept and would not eat. Elkanah's response — well-intentioned but insufficient — 'Don't I mean more to you than ten sons?' — reveals the gap between his love and her need. Some griefs cannot be addressed by the love of a husband; they require the intervention of God.\n\nHannah's prayer in 1 Samuel 1:10-11 is the model of covenant prayer: she prays in her heart, her lips move but no sound is heard, and she makes a specific vow — 'Lord Almighty, if you will only look on your servant's misery and remember me, and not forget your servant but give her a son, then I will give him to the Lord for all the days of his life, and no razor will ever be used on his head.' The Nazirite vow. The child she is asking for, she is simultaneously offering back. The prayer is not a transaction; it is an act of surrender clothed in supplication.\n\nEli's misreading of Hannah — 'How long are you going to stay drunk? Put away your wine' — is one of the most significant pastoral failures in the Old Testament. The man responsible for Israel's spiritual wellbeing cannot distinguish between inebriation and intense prayer. When Hannah explains herself, Eli's response recovers: 'Go in peace, and may the God of Israel grant you what you have asked of him.' Whether Eli realises it or not, he is speaking a prophetic blessing over the birth of his own successor.\n\nHannah's song in 1 Samuel 2:1-10 is the theological centrepiece of the entire book — perhaps of the entire Historical Books. It is not a lullaby or a personal thanksgiving; it is a theological manifesto about the God who reverses human hierarchies: 'He raises the poor from the dust and lifts the needy from the ash heap.' The song anticipates the Magnificat of Mary in Luke 1, echoing Hannah's language almost verbatim. Both songs celebrate the same God — the one who overturns the proud and exalts the humble. And both songs are sung by women who received an impossible child.",
