      "hook": "The Philistines captured the ark of God and placed it in Dagon's temple as a trophy of their victory — and found their god face-down on the floor twice, the second time with his head and hands broken off.",
      "teaching": "1 Samuel 5 is theological comedy with deadly consequences. The Philistines capture the ark, place it in Dagon's temple at Ashdod next to the idol, and return the next morning to find Dagon face-down before the ark. They set him up again. The next morning he is face-down again, with his head and both hands broken off on the threshold. The narrative adds a parenthetical note: 'That is why to this day neither the priests of Dagon nor any others who enter Dagon's temple at Ashdod step on the threshold.' The god of the Philistines has literally prostrated himself before the ark of the Lord. The victory the Philistines thought they had won over Israel's God turns out to be a victory of Israel's God over Philistia's god — accomplished without a single Israelite soldier.\n\nThe ark's journey through Philistine cities — Ashdod, Gath, Ekron — is a tour of divine judgment. Each city receives the ark with terror and sends it to the next city with relief. Tumours break out wherever the ark goes. The five Philistine lords send for their priests and diviners who devise a remarkably sophisticated test: place the ark on a new cart, attach two cows that have never been yoked, separate the cows from their calves, and see which direction the cows go. If the cows go to Beth Shemesh against their natural instinct, it is the God of Israel's work. If they wander, it was coincidence. The cows go straight to Beth Shemesh, lowing all the way. Even Philistine diviners can construct a methodologically sound test of divine causation.\n\nSamuel's ministry in 1 Samuel 7 is the climax of the Samuel-as-judge narrative. He addresses Israel at Mizpah with one of the most direct theological demands in his career: 'If you are returning to the Lord with all your hearts, then rid yourselves of the foreign gods and the Ashtoreths and commit yourselves to the Lord and serve him only.' Israel does it — they put away their Baals and Ashtoreths and served the Lord only. This is the same act that had temporarily moved God to action in Judges 10:16. When Israel actually removes the foreign gods, God responds.\n\nThe Philistines attack during the assembly at Mizpah. Samuel sacrifices a whole burnt offering and cries out to the Lord. The Lord thunders with loud thunder against the Philistines and throws them into such a panic that Israel routs them. Samuel sets up a stone called 'Ebenezer' — 'Thus far the Lord has helped us.' It is the same name as the place where Israel had been defeated and the ark captured in chapter 4 — the theological geography is deliberate. The defeat at Ebenezer is answered by the victory at Ebenezer. What was lost when Israel treated the ark as a talisman is recovered when Israel actually repents and returns.",
