    "studyCard": {
      "title": "The King Who Fell on His Sword and the Man Who Strengthened Himself in God",
      "hook": "1 Samuel 28-31 runs two simultaneous stories in parallel — Saul's final night consulting a medium, and David's crisis at Ziklag — and the contrast between how they handle the worst moments of their lives is the book's final theological verdict on both men.",
      "teaching": "1 Samuel 28-31 is the last movement of the book — four chapters that bring Saul's story to its tragic conclusion and David's story to the threshold of kingship. The two narratives run in deliberate parallel: Saul goes to a medium at night in disguise; David finds the city burned and his men ready to stone him. Both men face the worst night of their leadership careers. Saul's response and David's response are the theological contrast that concludes the book's argument.\n\nSaul's response to crisis in chapter 28 reveals the endpoint of a long process of spiritual deterioration. When God stops answering, he goes to a medium. When the medium produces an apparition of Samuel, he receives confirmation of everything Samuel told him while living. There is no repentance, no turning to God, no acceptance of divine judgment as Eli had accepted it. There is only collapse — physically, psychologically, spiritually. The woman of Endor shows more compassion for him than anyone in the narrative, pressing food on him until he eats. He leaves to fight a battle he has just been told he will lose.\n\nDavid's response to crisis in chapter 30 is the theological climax of the entire fugitive narrative. When his city burns and his men turn against him, 'David strengthened himself in the Lord his God.' Before asking for information, he sought the relationship. Before requesting strategy, he re-established the foundation. And then he enquired of the Lord, received guidance, pursued, and won a complete victory. The contrast with Saul could not be more complete: same type of crisis, same human isolation, completely opposite theological response.\n\nSaul's death in chapter 31 is the final word on what happens to a leader who replaces divine direction with personal agenda. He dies not by David's hand — David had been careful about that — and not by God's direct action, but by his own sword, having asked his armour-bearer to do it first. The man who had rejected God's word ends his life having rejected his armour-bearer's obedience and falling on his own weapon. Jonathan's death on the same day is the book's most painful element: the best character in the narrative dies with the worst, because he was loyal to his father even unto death.",
      "keyVerse": "But David strengthened himself in the Lord his God. — 1 Samuel 30:6 (NIV)",
      "memoryPrompt": "1 Samuel ends with Saul falling on his sword and David strengthening himself in God — the two responses to the worst possible circumstances defining the two kinds of leader the book has been comparing since chapter 13.",
      "challengeFact": "1 Samuel 31:2 records that among those killed in battle was Jonathan — the covenant friend of David, the man who had been next in line for the throne, who had helped David multiple times at great personal cost — and his death on the same day as his father Saul is recorded in a single verse with no emotional commentary, leaving the reader to bring all of chapters 18-20 to bear on the weight of that single name."
    },
